[recv] {"type": "message_end", "message": {"role": "assistant", "content": [{"type": "thinking", "thinking": "**Analyzing test coverage issues**\n\nI'm considering whether the existing tests are comprehensive. There were several false positives in the build report before our test, suggesting some tests might not have run. It seems \"attempt used 1 no newly covered\" indicates that newly added files weren't selected for coverage. I wonder if the harness report didn't include our test because it was untracked. Maybe I should modify an existing test instead of creating a new one since the untrack might be affecting our results.\n\n**Examining class naming and coverage**\n\nI'm checking the naming convention, particularly the class `RequestSpecificationImplInner_sessionId_closure11Test`. The rule about replacing `$` with \"Inner\" before the name makes sense since there’s an existing convention. But I wonder if the class isn't running because a JUnit test method can throw Throwable, and JUnit does support that.\n\nI'm also thinking about method handling. If `privateLookupIn` fails due to native-image limitations, it could mean no Java coverage. The \"no newly covered\" might stem from a dynamic-access report during JVM tests, even if the test fails. Perhaps I should create a Java test in the internal package.\n\n**Considering test package constraints**\n\nI'm thinking about the rule that tests need to stay outside the library package. I'm not sure if I can work around this, like using `sun.misc.Unsafe`, but that seems off-limits. I wonder if `MethodHandles.publicLookup()` would help, but it can't access package-private members. \n\nWhat if I compile the test class in a non-library package but define a nested class in the same package? However, I remember that a Java file can only belong to one package. Using `MethodHandles.Lookup.IMPL_LOOKUP` through Unsafe also seems like a lot of trouble.\n\n**Investigating method invocation**\n\nI'm wondering if invoking a package-private static method directly with MethodHandles might not produce the usual invokestatic in the test bytecode. Instead, it could show as reflection, mapping the call site differently. When I call it through MethodHandle, the stack frame line might actually be “DirectMethodHandleAccessor.invoke.” I find it interesting how the details of bytecode behavior can shift depending on the method invocation. This topic has a lot of layers to untangle!\n\n**Analyzing reflection versus MethodHandles**\n\nI'm considering that class loading with Class.forName still shows in the class$ frame and should be counted. Although, I'm curious if the agent overlooks reflective calls via synthetic methods when invoked reflectively. \n\nMaybe using Java reflection with Method.invoke could offer a different approach, but that goes against the established rule. User feedback hints that MethodHandles might not suffice due to package-private methods. Reflection with setAccessible seems more promising but might need metadata for closure class methods. Creating a test helper class within the same package could be a viable solution!\n\n**Considering package restrictions**\n\nThe rule states to keep outside the library package, but that's tricky since existing tests are within `io_rest_assured` and aren't interchangeable. I'm thinking about utilizing `groovy.lang.MetaClass` to invoke the static method, as the Groovy runtime might be able to access package-private methods. This approach could help me navigate around the limitations while still adhering to the testing rules. It’s a bit of a workaround, but I want to ensure I’m doing it right!\n\n**Considering native image behavior**\n\nI think I’m looking into how to avoid using reflect-config in native images. The dynamic coverage from the agent should be enough, but I’m concerned that the Native Image might fail if `Cookie$Builder` metadata isn’t included. I’m also wondering about using Class.forName for application or library classes—will that work if the type is reachable? It seems like for arbitrary classes in a native image, that function needs reflection metadata.", "thinkingSignature": "{\"id\":\"rs_0a40001413567ff2016a2799fee268819380acdc3a3f78e908\",\"type\":\"reasoning\",\"content\":[],\"encrypted_content\":\"gAAAAABqJ5oxmW2-h592QCJLqnOuHnWYE5PNs9j6b3m8wlPZeYL5d4rTWpszycsQM7zOCaCidLQ4iqb1F2i_pA7gYPYQ2dUBurbZT4ssarf8q2yhRdWnlhgx8NIdqdoczahc4xMJf1cRS975nE-dMN18-IR1Vq8U6oYPkDtP_2hLSNQgbHC0O71aX54QSQIHkMUQ7KGDn-ChUTnoSvcPBhGAaAd-8H5tCVwd07CQhU5s40vJD2y1fySMLOu0bbhpumPrYCTiO7gGcQ-8Mjns0VsnuyBoPiPi8eQPsxeS2k7IE-IGqp5H-lBsAxuCgwbeKji1nrjY8BxApEG50MCOk_NRe4DLQDY1cdSaBZezzUrCwL_abWKmAoDtRzwqgln4zLq5d91HL_bRQU6aPBExFZuGFul10xo7W2JRC_uoBGrrFSjKDRIDinKcP6U2IX2hIopyoXlB9rZzMCK9FAyMAoVS8bNG3N5U1UnqQQYCalUm825tpxlnrQ4IhSt6I48bSOHck532RDlRf7qX95Iq3d-3L369EQzdhPmANaNPohRI99zKYymdZBUJUzIcpwqM3VDRH43UaS-EKA840veDm6iaC5GlymOr0IBb7u5Gy6E4JMuLoXEhVjsh8MdP8GJq4YKTBMd6cOhEpkWMZv3CCzO_0zhr6SUCM_RceNClk4fxWVzSxgb6ZjYenCZksf1AIpgS8-Z05p_G7qqLIutXtp4zqmBKmVRlx-XdByjD3nOmTWo8k4Tkn-RR2EmaIYEku3fHMI76imAgJ2FGEwjfJIDdI2jkKaDNjIYrCCQajpWEXPskfVwJQmdjharE2Z5tPfozK3LHZeJIFljCL704_YR_lki8TEVsMByce4bTh9G_RiJgAGWlC3zAwf85MjIHnhJASxZ5uFZx8GG47vF-HzynGV5Qv32mjp8AbZIHUXeXtgFjzm5HZTWZEVN8SMR5JTQvC4-uHNzPSiaXn5mqqLbNE_Y1hgd4B1QYWfIyR8bYeRzwKQ3wawo3hqszTqY4zFT7dCy9VCHi_a0nnV2MKvh-_f90t5_A6L4vwYqbzAeuAqamWYcJuzJtVV6ddrbkD2-_KqExYOo9uEiaRbVUwKqkCZQ_utxgdbspyNhqUGwFoJ-oXYOK9D5RcIxl3PgunBNv982LKgp70tjxN8HA2_sr_Ic2eeA6I7j6kSp8k78cMVMpLIsj4RwsQlOWZW3gWnl2l-WMUfkrzsfFq9s-rolcEMVntN6YeC7OB07ilIQnF7xgyZY0oc11h9AWl_bB2e5uW3AOnTFKQDUjiUG-37S2gQfI2nuhydcjqr5zRJvs8di0uXM2GiXMj9MmXTcsiTJyXUOaQM1FUS-Wb3xg6uIJaulUcTcmKennT7jPK1BxHm4PR_SM88grSu8f7Wq4GLvLrZhEMCPccb6k9cdmFGVQt4liL3Lx5aWB8GOxcRcdNnU-Oz6MVUnwiR93vlCXmjxsuUZyNcEHeF9V0KvvJZR9u6ght4fTUfWfgSicyVWkg6T90D62jXEMZ3-0rig4QvfF3wvgXnCLuOb4Ol8kIE18Qw_nxi4hOB9l97kFmIW11QpyAATYho6PLciJhwkVvjCuI7Y71kZaFy3vtlodxqErXZ5oi0YkMAXjDnUZmcZ4siluPRSgahFeHnKNkSCSVoosb29lDZL6vcm5XaHlmellwE_QLTSNYPFDrmB-XKHAoHEYDQAdbFYDL_D3