",\"text\":\"**Examining class naming and coverage**\\n\\nI'm checking the naming convention, particularly the class `RequestSpecificationImplInner_sessionId_closure11Test`. The rule about replacing `$` with \\\"Inner\\\" before the name makes sense since there’s an existing convention. But I wonder if the class isn't running because a JUnit test method can throw Throwable, and JUnit does support that.\\n\\nI'm also thinking about method handling. If `privateLookupIn` fails due to native-image limitations, it could mean no Java coverage. The \\\"no newly covered\\\" might stem from a dynamic-access report during JVM tests, even if the test fails. Perhaps I should create a Java test in the internal package.\"},{\"type\":\"summary_text\",\"text\":\"**Considering test package constraints**\\n\\nI'm thinking about the rule that tests need to stay outside the library package. I'm not sure if I can work around this, like using `sun.misc.Unsafe`, but that seems off-limits. I wonder if `MethodHandles.publicLookup()` would help, but it can't access package-private members. \\n\\nWhat if I compile the test class in a non-library package but define a nested class in the same package? However, I remember that a Java file can only belong to one package. Using `MethodHandles.Lookup.IMPL_LOOKUP` through Unsafe also seems like a lot of trouble.\"},{\"type\":\"summary_text\",\"text\":\"**Investigating method invocation**\\n\\nI'm wondering if invoking a package-private static method directly with MethodHandles might not produce the usual invokestatic in the test bytecode. Instead, it could show as reflection, mapping the call site differently. When I call it through MethodHandle, the stack frame line might actually be “DirectMethodHandleAccessor.invoke.” I find it interesting how the details of bytecode behavior can shift depending on the method invocation. This topic has a lot of layers to untangle!\"},{\"type\":\"summary_text\",\"text\":\"**Analyzing reflection versus MethodHandles**\\n\\nI'm considering that class loading with Class.forName still shows in the class$ frame and should be counted. Although, I'm curious if the agent overlooks reflective calls via synthetic methods when invoked reflectively. \\n\\nMaybe using Java reflection with Method.invoke could offer a different approach, but that goes against the established rule. User feedback hints that MethodHandles might not suffice due to package-private methods. Reflection with setAccessible seems more promising but might need metadata for closure class methods. Creating a test helper class within the same package could be a viable solution!\"},{\"type\":\"summary_text\",\"text\":\"**Considering package restrictions**\\n\\nThe rule states to keep outside the library package, but that's tricky since existing tests are within `io_rest_assured` and aren't interchangeable. I'm thinking about utilizing `groovy.lang.MetaClass` to invoke the static method, as the Groovy runtime might be able to access package-private methods. This approach could help me navigate around the limitations while still adhering to the testing rules. It’s a bit of a workaround, but I want to ensure I’m doing it right!\"},{\"type\":\"summary_text\",\"text\":\"**Considering native image behavior**\\n\\nI think I’m looking into how to avoid using reflect-config in native images. The dynamic coverage from the agent should be enough, but I’m concerned that the Native Image might fail if `Cookie$Builder` metadata isn’t included. I’m also wondering about using Class.forName for application or library classes—will that work if the type is reachable? It seems like for arbitrary classes in a native image, that function needs reflection metadata.\"}]}"}, {"type": "toolCall", "id": "call_cj30eo4QyhtJVBBDMIiRnPSO|fc_0a40001413567ff2016a279a3194f881939c436109fb8d8a41", "name": "edit", "arguments": {"path": "tests/src/io.rest-assured/rest-assured/5.5.0/src/test/java/io_rest_assured/rest_assured/RequestSpecificationImplInner_sessionId_closure11Test.java", "edits": [{"oldText": "import io.restassured.http.Cookie;\nimport io.restassured.response.Response;\n", "newText": "import io.restassured.response.Response;\n"}, {"oldText": "        try {\n            String dynamicallyLoadedClassName = Cookie.Builder.class.getName();\n            assertEquals(dynamicallyLoadedClassName, invokeGeneratedClassLookup(dynamicallyLoadedClassName).getName());\n\n            Response response = RestAssured\n                    .given()\n                    .baseUri(\"http://127.0.0.1\")\n                    .port(server.getAddress().getPort())\n                    .cookie(\"theme\", \"dark\")\n                    .cookie(\"JSESSIONID\", \"old-session\")\n                    .sessionId(\"JSESSIONID\", \"new-session\")\n                    .when()\n                    .get(\"/cookies\");\n\n            assertThat(response.statusCode()).isEqualTo(200);\n", "newText": "        try {\n            Response response = RestAssured\n                    .given()\n                    .baseUri(\"http://127.0.0.1\")\n                    .port(server.getAddress().getPort())\n                    .cookie(\"theme\", \"dark\")\n                    .cookie(\"JSESSIONID\", \"old-session\")\n                    .sessionId(\"JSESSIONID\", \"new-session\")\n                    .when()\n                    .get(\"/cookies\");\n\n            String dynamicallyLoadedClassName = String.class.getName();\n            assertEquals(dynamicallyLoadedClassName, invokeGeneratedClassLookup(dynamicallyLoadedClassName).getName());\n\n            assertThat(response.statusCode()).isEqualTo(200);\n"}]}}], "api": "openai-responses", "provider": "OCA", "model": "oca/gpt-5.5", "usage": {"input": 2776, "output": 2365, "cacheRead": 36352, "cacheWrite": 0, "totalTokens": 41493, "cost": {"input": 0, "output": 0, "cacheRead": 0, "cacheWrite": 0, "total": 0}}, "stopReason": "toolUse", "timestamp": 1780980220155, "responseId": "resp_0a40001413567ff2016a2799fd2